        yeah, i agree with a lot of the comments here that the chart has hit a low. there is plenty of good music charting, much better than some other recent years, but it feels like ACR has collapsed in on itself. songs charting for over a year in the top 40 and songs dating back decades thriving on the charts while fresh, new exciting hits reflecting the musical landscape we're in right now, get booted down the charts on their 10th week unless they're a mammoth hit. i hope the OCC do something about this (adopt billboard's recurrent rule in my opinion). not even to be negative, but this is just something that needs fixing and i don't think many disagree.

        with that being said, mutt in the top 40 is cute! and love me not entering the top 20 warms my heart. not as fussed about show me love or carry you home. selena and benny managed three entries in the end, that album confused me but i always enjoy what selena brings to pop, it's always interesting to hear. additionally, here for tell me and it isn't perfect returning to the top 40 and hope they can reach new peaks. the giver has also grown on me loads.

        It's the first time I have seen comments about how the charts are compiled and the system not working.  I have a solution that is practical and gets rid of ACR completely.  Instead of counting "units" count Retail Sales instead.  What I mean by Retail Sales is the cost per unit to the public. So for downloads you count the 99p (etc) and for vinyl the actual price of each one sold. Same with CDs.  As for streams, they can be worked out by the price paid for a monthly subscription divide by a typical family downloads (currently around 2,000 per month). So a £10.99 subscription at 2,000 would give a stream price of 0,005p per stream.  For add funded streams, this would be much lower.  Say 0.001p a stream.

        At the moment, 100 units of CD and 100 of Vinyl and 100 downloads amounts to 300 units.

        But 100 CD at £3.99p 100 Vinyl at £10.99 and 100 downloads at 99p as you can see are not the same. But 400 sales equivalent streams would beat the 300 other units. 

        However, 400 stream units would amount to just £2!

        The biggest effect would be the albums.  For example, a £27.99 vinyl selling just 10 copies would produce £279.90 of sales.

        Currently, if you buy a CD, download, or vinyl, or any format that is physical, you can affect the chart. But no matter how many times you stream a record, you don't have any effect on sales, unless several other people do the same!  The Retail Sales Chart would stop that

        2,073 digital downloads of Alex amount to £2,052.27p at 99p. For example, (OCC figures).

        The Streams on Spotify would give Alex £20,978.12p

        The 100 position on Spotify currently gives a sale of just £3,440.03p.

        Of course, these are based on one streaming rate of £0.005p.  As Spotify probably combines free streams, these would need to be separated.  The other streaming sites don't give figures, but the OCC will know these.

        The ACR system does work. I know a lot of people are upset that songs like Beautiful Things (4) are getting such impressive chart hold given their age, but if it is popular then it should just stick high up. There's no reason why older songs can't stay in the chart if they're still popular. Yes - things were out of hand when Sabrina Carpenter consistently occupied the top three spots, but that's harmless compared to what the charts were like without the three-song rule and ACR - Ed Sheeran with the top 10 all to himself! My only criticism of the ACR system is the almost inability for older songs to "escape" ACR - they have to almost double popularity. This percentage should be lowered - but otherwise the system is pretty cool!
